Why AGPL
--------

The point is not to forbid use. Use it, study it, fork it, run it on anything.

The point is that it cannot be **enclosed**. Distribute a modified version and
the source goes with it — and under §13, that holds for network services too, so
"we host it, you rent it, source stays ours" is not available either. Plain GPL
leaves that door open; AGPL does not.

This camera was abandoned by the company that built it and kept alive for years
by the people who owned one. What that community rebuilt should not be closed
back up by anybody — us included.

Two consequences worth knowing before you build on this:

- AGPL code cannot be merged back into `gennyble/lri-rs`, which is ISC. Anything
  offered upstream has to be limited to changes we can also release under ISC.
- Some organisations ban AGPL dependencies outright. That is a deliberate trade:
  reach given up in exchange for the guarantee above.


